body: Can you get the dependencies  and then regenerate? We use goimports to find these packages so if they exist on the FS then the imports will be present too. You should be able to get list you need from the message that is printed at the end of the generation step.

Note: there's nothing in my ~/go

I ran:

    $ go get github.com/go-openapi/errors github.com/go-openapi/loads
    $ go get github.com/go-openapi/runtime github.com/go-openapi/runtime/flagext github.com/go-openapi/runtime/middleware github.com/go-openapi/runtime/security github.com/go-openapi/validate github.com/jessevdk/go-flags github.com/tylerb/graceful

If I re-generate it appears to fix the problem:

    $ ./bin/swagger generate server -A gopurge --default-scheme=https -t src/gen swagger.yml
    ...
    $ go run src/gen/cmd/gopurge-server/main.go
    2018/04/16 12:06:49 Serving gopurge at http://127.0.0.1:45421
I guess it's working as intended but caught me by surprise. Maybe a note in the installation instructions would be helpful

body:
Hi @casualjim, @fredbi - here's a simple way to reproduce the problem that Adam reported:

```bash
mkdir test && cd test
mkdir -p src/gen
export GOPATH=`pwd`

# Write swagger.yml based on contents below:
cat swagger.yml
```
```yaml
swagger: "2.0"

consumes:
- application/json
produces:
- application/json

info:
  title: testthing
  description: testthing
  version: 0.0.1

schemes:
- http

paths:
  /foo:
    post:
      tags:
        - Bar
      operationId: fooBar
      responses:
        429:
          $ref: '#/responses/RateLimitedResp'

responses:
  RateLimitedResp:
    description: Rate Limited
    headers:
      X-Rate-Limit-Reset:
        type: string
        format: date-time
    schema:
      $ref: "#/definitions/responseBody"

definitions:
  responseBody:
    type: object
    required:
      - httpStatus
    properties:
      httpStatus:
        type: integer
        format: int32
        readOnly: true
```
```bash
latestv=$(curl -s https://api.github.com/repos/go-swagger/go-swagger/releases/latest | jq -r .tag_name)
curl -o swagger -L'#' https://github.com/go-swagger/go-swagger/releases/download/$latestv/swagger_$(echo `uname`|tr '[:upper:]' '[:lower:]')_amd64
chmod +x swagger

./swagger generate server -A testhing -t src/gen swagger.yml

pushd . && cd src/gen/ && dep init && popd  # Pull down dependencies

go run src/gen/cmd/testhing-server/main.go
# # gen/restapi/operations/bar
# src/gen/restapi/operations/bar/foo_bar_responses.go:27:18: undefined: strfmt
head -n 30 src/gen/restapi/operations/bar/foo_bar_responses.go
```

```golang
// Code generated by go-swagger; DO NOT EDIT.

package bar

// This file was generated by the swagger tool.
// Editing this file might prove futile when you re-run the swagger generate command

import (
	"net/http"

	"github.com/go-openapi/runtime"

	models "gen/models"
)

// FooBarTooManyRequestsCode is the HTTP code returned for type FooBarTooManyRequests
const FooBarTooManyRequestsCode int = 429

/*FooBarTooManyRequests Rate Limited

swagger:response fooBarTooManyRequests
*/
type FooBarTooManyRequests struct {
	/*

	 */
	XRateLimitReset strfmt.DateTime `json:"X-Rate-Limit-Reset"` // <-- strftime used but not imported

	/*
	  In: Body
```

My conclusion: the `date-time` format under the `X-Rate-Limit-Reset` Response header isn't correctly triggering the import of `github.com/go-openapi/strfmt`. This dependency *is* correctly being pulled down by the `dep` invocation.

Please let me know if I'm missing something, or if there's a known work around.

Thanks!
haven't tried this yet, but can you regenerate after you've done `dep init`

Thanks for the prompt reply. I get the same behavior:

```bash
# ...
pushd . && cd src/gen/ && dep init && popd  # Pull down dependencies

./swagger generate server -A testhing -t src/gen swagger.yml

go run src/gen/cmd/testhing-server/main.go

# # gen/restapi/operations/bar
# src/gen/restapi/operations/bar/foo_bar_responses.go:27:18: undefined: strfmt
```
Dependencies must be installed before generation. Goimports cannot resolve strfmt and removes the import line.
Ah, now I see. Thanks. Kind of curious that goimports cannot find the stuff that `dep` pulled in, but using `go get github.com/go-openapi/strfmt` resolved it.

because dep builds a vendor directory 
if this vendor is not in your generation target, goimport cannot find it
